"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/908878","Department for Education","false","2018-05-31","<p>Although there are no plans to introduce any new GCSEs in this Parliament, the government is open to considering a proposal for a British Sign Language (BSL) GCSE for possible introduction in the longer term. We have indicated this to Signature, the awarding organisation proposing to develop a GCSE in BSL, and the National Deaf Children’s Society.</p><p> </p><p>Any new GCSE would need to meet the rigorous expectations for subject content, which are set by the department. It would also need to meet the expectations for assessment and regulatory requirements, which are set by Ofqual, the independent qualifications regulator. The department and Ofqual will consider carefully any proposals put forward in due course.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton",,"2018-05-31T12:43:19.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/908878/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/908878/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/908878/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-21","Sign Language: GCSE","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what consideration they have given to offering British Sign Language as a language choice for examination in the national curriculum.","false","Biography information for Lord Bruce of Bennachie",,"Lord Bruce of Bennachie","HL8040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/908879","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-06-05","<p>British Sign Language (BSL) was recognised as a language in its own right by the UK Government in March 2003. All Government departments are under a legal duty under the Equality Act 2010 to make reasonable adjustments when communicating with disabled people, which might include the provision of BSL interpreters.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe",,"2018-06-05T16:02:21.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/908879/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/908879/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/908879/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-21","Government Departments: Sign Language","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they recognise sign language as a valid and legal means of communication with all Government departments.","false","Biography information for Lord Bruce of Bennachie",,"Lord Bruce of Bennachie","HL8041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/908880","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-06-05","<p>The Welsh Language (Wales) Measure 2011 and the Gaelic Language (Scotland) Act 2005, recognise the Welsh and Gaelic languages respectively and provide for the status of the languages in each of those devolved territories. The Cornish language was recognised by the Government in 2002 under the Council of Europe’s European Charter for Regional or Minority languages.</p><p>The Government already recognises British Sign Language as a language in its own right. The Equality Act 2010 also places a duty on public bodies, employers, and service providers to provide services in BSL and other formats when it is reasonable to do so. In addition the Public Sector Equality Duty also requires public bodies to have due regard to the needs of all those with protected characteristics. We do not believe that any additional legislation would add to that</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Buscombe",,"2018-06-05T16:27:53.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/908880/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/908880/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/908880/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-21","Sign Language","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to support any proposed legislation to give recognition to British and Irish Sign Language on the same basis as Welsh, Gaelic and Cornish.","false","Biography information for Lord Bruce of Bennachie",,"Lord Bruce of Bennachie","HL8042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/908881","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-06-05","<p>The information requested to answer the question in full, is not centrally available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe",,"2018-06-05T16:09:49.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/908881/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/908881/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/908881/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-21","Sign Language","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how much they spend in supporting sign language users across the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Bruce of Bennachie",,"Lord Bruce of Bennachie","HL8043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/908882","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-06-05","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that all families who lose a child are given the support they need. That is why we have announced the establishment of a Children’s Funeral Fund for England, with the intention that no bereaved family will have to pay for the essential costs of burying or cremating their child. The detailed policy is under development and will be announced in due course.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie","HL8045 ; HL8046 ; HL8047 ; HL8048","2018-06-05T11:40:16.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/908882/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/908882/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/908882/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-05-21","Funerals: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to publish further details on how the Children's Funeral Fund for England will operate; and if so, when.","false","Biography information for Baroness Burt of Solihull",,"Baroness Burt of Solihull","HL8044"
