"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909058","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-30","<p>The Environment Agency requires operators to continuously monitor atmospheric emissions of total particulate matter. In practice, the vast majority of particulate matter emitted by incinerators is likely to be PM10 or less, which includes PM2.5, PM1.0 and PM0.1.</p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley",,"2018-05-30T16:45:39.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909058/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909058/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909058/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-21","Incinerators","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 16 May 2018 to Question 142751, on incinerators, what other sizes of particulates the term other particulates refers to.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","146090"
