"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909082","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-25","<p>Data on how many complications resulting from medical abortions were reported in England and Wales in 2017 is not yet available. 2017 abortion data will be published on 7 June 2018.</p><p> </p><p>The Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists’ 2011 clinical guideline on the Care of Women Requesting Induced Abortion highlights that abortion using both medical and surgical methods is a safe procedure for which major complications and mortality are rare at all gestations. The guideline notes that medical abortion with mifepristone and misoprostol is associated with a longer duration of bleeding, more pain and gastrointestinal adverse effects, and a higher likelihood of being incomplete than vacuum aspiration under general anaesthetic up to 14 weeks of gestation. A copy of the guideline can be viewed online at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.rcog.org.uk/globalassets/documents/guidelines/abortion-guideline_web_1.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.rcog.org.uk/globalassets/documents/guidelines/abortion-guideline_web_1.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>Information on the number of women diagnosed with complications following a surgical and medical abortion in each of the last five years for which data is published is set out in the following table.</p><p> </p><p>Legal abortions - complications by procedure, residents of England and Wales, 2012-16</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Total all procedures</p></td><td><p>Surgical</p></td><td><p>Medical</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>278</p></td><td><p>91</p></td><td><p>187</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>235</p></td><td><p>83</p></td><td><p>152</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>330</p></td><td><p>101</p></td><td><p>229</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>294</p></td><td><p>85</p></td><td><p>209</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>294</p></td><td><p>88</p></td><td><p>206</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Note:</p><p>Data on complications is collected on HSA4 forms which provide a notification of each abortion.</p><p>Complications which arise after the form has been completed will not be included in the official statistics.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","146199 ; 146200 ; 146202","2018-05-25T10:38:28.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909082/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909082/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909082/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-21","Abortion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many women were diagnosed with complications following a (a) surgical and (b) medical abortion in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","146203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909083","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-25","<p>The Government’s priority is to ensure that women who require abortion services have access to safe, high-quality care. Abortions in England must be performed under the legal framework set by the Abortion Act 1967. We are not currently in a position to recommend that the home be approved as a class of place under Section 1(3)(a) of the Abortion Act in England. However, we are keeping the position under review, including reviewing the available evidence and having regard to the ongoing legal proceedings concerning home use in Scotland.</p><p> </p><p>The evidence shows that the use of misoprostol is safe for women receiving abortion treatment who have no contraindications. Common physical side effects include abdominal pain, diarrhoea, dizziness, headache, nausea, rash and vomiting. Uncommon side effects are abnormal vaginal bleeding, pyrexia (high temperature) and uterine cramping.</p><p> </p><p>We are not aware of any assessment of the psychological impact of passing a fetus at home but in 2011 the World Health Organization published a systematic review, Comparative effectiveness, safety and acceptability of medical abortion at home and in a clinic. On acceptability, studies were examined that looked at satisfaction with the method, the likelihood of choosing the method again and the likelihood of recommending medical abortion to a friend. For medical abortions completed at home the average satisfaction rate was 88.4% and analysis showed no difference in satisfaction rates between women taking misoprostol at home or in clinic. In England, most women undergoing early medical abortion leave the clinic after taking the misoprostol and complete the procedure at home. A copy of the review can be viewed online at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.who.int/bulletin/volumes/89/5/10-084046/en/" target="_blank">http://www.who.int/bulletin/volumes/89/5/10-084046/en/</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","146197 ; 146198 ; 146201","2018-05-25T10:29:25.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909083/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909083/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909083/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-21","Abortion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment his Department has made of the psychological impact of passing a foetus at home on a woman who has had an early medical abortion.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","146204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909084","Home Office","false","2018-05-24","<p>We have not received any application for funding in respect of the wedding of the Duke and Duchess of Sussex. Officials are in regular contact with the police force and will provide any assistance necessary should the Police and Crime Commissioner choose to submit an application. As I set out in my response to the Hon Member for Edinburgh East, I will carefully consider any such application.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-05-24T14:50:11.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909084/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909084/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909084/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-21","Henry, Duke of Sussex: Marriage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 15 May 2018 to Question 142892 on Prince Harry: Marriage, whether since that Answer (a) Thames Valley Police or (b) the Thames Valley Police and Crime Commissioner submitted an application to his Department for Special Grant funding for additional costs associated with policing the royal wedding.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","146336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909085","Treasury","false","2018-05-24","<p>The details that HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) collects from taxpayers on their VAT returns are not specific enough to provide the information requested.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-05-24T15:51:29.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909085/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909085/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909085/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-21","Gold: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the cost to the public purse has been of the value added tax exemption for gold investment coins in (a) 2015-16 and (b) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","146281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909086","Treasury","false","2018-05-25","<p>The details that HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) collects from taxpayers on their VAT returns are not specific enough to provide this information.</p><p> </p><p>The sale and chartering of helicopters is only zero-rated for VAT purposes when:</p><p> </p><ul><li><p>They are used by airlines who operate for reward chiefly on international routes; or</p></li></ul><p> </p><ul><li><p>They are used by state institutions, and have a weight of not less than 8,000 kg.</p></li></ul>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-05-25T10:43:06.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909086/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909086/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909086/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-21","Helicopters: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the cost to the public purse has been of the value added tax exemption for the sale and chartering of helicopters in (a) 2015-16 and (b) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","146282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909087","Treasury","false","2018-05-25","<p>The details that HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) collects from taxpayers on their VAT returns are not specific enough to provide this information.</p><p> </p><p>The sale and chartering of civil aeroplanes is only zero-rated for VAT purposes when:</p><p> </p><ul><li><p>They are used by airlines who operate for reward chiefly on international routes; or</p></li></ul><p> </p><ul><li><p>They are used by state institutions, and have a weight of not less than 8,000 kg.</p></li></ul>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-05-25T10:45:42.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909087/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909087/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909087/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-21","Aircraft: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the cost to the public purse has been of the value added exemption for the sale or chartering of civil aeroplanes in (a) 2015-16 and (b) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","146283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909088","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-24","<p>The average amount of SMI loan repayable upon the sale of the home is estimated at around £1,200 after a year, increasing to around £4,000 after 5 years.</p><p> </p><p>DWP has produced tables that provide examples of how SMI loans might accrue over time and these are included in the Frequently Asked Questions that are issued to claimants after they have had the information call with Serco. In many cases the recovery of SMI loans will impact the beneficiaries of the recipients of SMI loans. Without the provision of the SMI loan it is possible that the property would have been repossessed by the mortgage lender.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-05-24T10:32:11.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909088/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909088/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909088/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-21","Support for Mortgage Interest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 21 May 2018 to Question 133903, what assessment her Department has made of the financial effect of the loss of equity caused by repaying the loan that has now replaced Support for Mortgage Interest at the point of sale of the home.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","146263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909089","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-24","<p>The Independent Case Examiner’s Office will receive funding for thirteen additional staff during the 2018/19 financial year. Decisions as to how those resources are deployed rest with the Independent Case Examiner’s Office. Given the range and compexity of the complaints examined by the Office and the demand led nature of the service it provides, it is not possible to provide reliable predictions on how this will impact on overall waiting times.</p><p> </p><p>Responses to the ICE Customer Satisfaction survey are anonymised and as such its is not possible to determine what proportion of WASPI complainants were satisfied with the service provided by the ICE Office.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-05-24T10:32:13.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909089/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909089/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909089/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-21","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 17 May 2018 to Question 143651 on State Retirement Pensions: Females, how much additional resource has been provided to the Independent Case Examiners Office for 2018/2019; what effect this additional resource is expected to have on waiting times for complaints to be completed; and what proportion of those who responded to the ICE customer survey whose complaint related to WASPI said that they were satisfied with the service they received.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","146091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909090","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-06-05","<p>The Treaty on the Functioning of the EU (TFEU) places restrictions on the introduction of measures that impair the free movement of goods within the EU market.</p><p> </p><p>Where there are EU harmonising measures relevant to the movement of fur – including the Animal By-Products Regulation in respect of untreated fur and the Seal Products Regulation – any derogation from those in the form of a national restriction would need to meet the requirements of Article 114 TFEU or any specific safeguard measure included in the harmonising legislation. This would involve notifying the measures to the European Commission who would need to be satisfied that the issue is “specific to that Member State”, that it would not amount to a means of arbitrary discrimination or a disguised restriction on trade, or an obstacle to the functioning of the internal market.</p><p> </p><p>Introducing a ban in the absence of such consent where it is needed would breach Article 114 TFEU.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-06-05T15:09:03.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909090/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909090/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909090/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-21","Furs: Import Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will seek legal advice on whether the UK can introduce a ban on the import of fur while the UK is a member of the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","146054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909091","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-24","<p>The requested information for the numbers of FTE (full time equivalent) employees based in Oldham Job Centre since 2010 is:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>November 2010 – </strong>168.35 FTE</p><p><strong>April 2011 – </strong>153.01 FTE</p><p><strong>April 2012 – </strong>128.08 FTE</p><p><strong>April 2013 – </strong>134.57 FTE</p><p><strong>April 2014 – </strong>136.29 FTE</p><p><strong>April 2015 – </strong>128.93 FTE</p><p><strong>April 2016 – </strong>79.99 FTE<strong>*</strong></p><p><strong>April 2017 – </strong>73.77 FTE<strong>* </strong></p><p><strong>2018 (as of May) – </strong>120.76 FTE</p><p> </p><p>* The lower FTE figures at April 2016 and April 2017 reflect natural attrition (resignations, promotions and transfers), a Voluntary Early Severance package (part of a national DWP scheme), and the continuing improvement in employment figures. From April 2017 onwards additional staff were recruited due to the roll-out of Universal Credit in Oldham, in July 2017.</p><p> </p><p>All figures are rounded to the nearest decimal point due to DWP’s FTE calculation process.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-05-24T16:04:06.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909091/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909091/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909091/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-21","Jobcentres: Oldham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many FTE employees were based in Oldham Job Centre in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","146310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909092","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-24","<p>The law does not set a time limit for notifying decisions, be they in relation to claims or applications for mandatory reconsideration. However, decision makers recognise the need to ensure that all decisions are notified without delay. Indeed, usually decision letters are generated automatically and sent immediately once the decision itself has been made.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-05-24T14:38:31.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909092/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909092/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909092/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-21","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether her Department has set a time limit for notifying claimants from the date of decision whether their (a) application and (b) mandatory reconsideration for Personal Independence Payment has been unsuccessful; and if she will take steps to ensure that unsuccessful claimants receive their decision in a timely manner.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","146295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909093","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-24","<p>The Department’s Work Programme does not have a contract covering just Greater Manchester, so the information can not be provided at the level of detail requested.</p><p> </p><p>However, there is a contract covering Greater Manchester, Chester and Warrington. The expenditure on this contract is shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>2016/17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>£m</p></td><td><p>£m</p></td><td><p>£m</p></td><td><p>£m</p></td><td><p>£m</p></td><td><p>£m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Greater Manchester, Chester &amp; Warrington</p></td><td><p>18</p></td><td><p>32</p></td><td><p>46</p></td><td><p>46</p></td><td><p>32</p></td><td><p>23</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p> </p><ol><li>The Work Programme started during 2011/12, therefore no data is available for 2010/11.</li></ol><p> </p><ol start="2"><li>The 2017/18 indicative total outturn cannot be released as the Department's accounts have yet to be finalised, audited and approved.</li></ol>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-05-24T16:04:10.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909093/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909093/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909093/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-21","Work Programme: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much money from the public purse was paid to work programme providers in Greater Manchester in each relevant year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","146311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909094","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-24","<p>Up until 31 December 2013 Bus Service Operators Grant (BSOG) was paid directly to bus operators and wasn’t split between commercially run or subsidised bus services. We are therefore unable to provide figures for this period. From 1 January 2014 local authorities have received funding equivalent to the level of BSOG which would otherwise have been paid to operators for running subsidised services. Details of the amounts paid to local authorities each year can be found on the “Payments to Local Authorities” tab on the relevant spreadsheets published on the <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/bus-services-grants-and-funding#bsog-spend" target="_blank">.gov</a> website.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-05-24T09:53:48.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909094/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909094/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909094/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-21","Bus Services: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much money from the public purse was spent on subsidised bus routes in Greater Manchester in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","146312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909095","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-24","<p>The Foreign Secretary spoke to his US counterpart about the President’s upcoming visit to London during his visit to Washington on 7 May. The Foreign Secretary made clear that we looked forward to welcoming President Trump in July.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-05-24T06:39:16.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909095/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909095/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909095/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-21","USA: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has had discussions with his US counterpart on appropriate (a) behaviour and (b language of the US president for his visit to the UK.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","146313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909096","Home Office","false","2018-05-25","<p>The EU Settlement Scheme is being designed with users in mind, and we are engaging with stakeholders who represent EU citizens in the UK to discuss and understand their needs. Our regular stakeholder groups include community representatives, employers, the EU27 consulates, and organisations representing vulnerable groups. We are developing a streamlined, user-friendly, digital application system, with multiple service options to meet the needs of a varied customer base, including additional support for the vulnerable.</p><p>We have launched a targeted communications campaign to maximise awareness and reassure EU citizens of our commitment to protect their rights and entitlements. Activity will increase as we approach the launch of the scheme before the end of this year.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","146061 ; 146062 ; 146063 ; 146064 ; 146065 ; 146066","2018-05-25T13:54:07.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909096/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909096/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/909096/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-21","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps his Department is taking to consult with EU citizens resident in the UK on the new IT system and process for applying for settled status.","false","Biography information for Ms Diane Abbott","Hackney North and Stoke Newington","Ms Diane Abbott","146060"
