"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907145","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-05-29","<p>The Government has recently strengthened the ability of local authorities to take action where landlords are failing to meet their obligations. This includes launching a national database of rogue landlords and property agents on 1 April 2018. A local housing authority must enter a landlord onto the database if they are subject to a banning order. They also have the discretion to enter a landlord onto the database if they have been convicted of a banning order offence or have received two or more civil penalties for banning order offences in a 12 month period. This could include resident landlords if they have been convicted of an offence under schedule 1 of the Housing and Planning Act 2016.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-05-29T16:07:16.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907145/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907145/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907145/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-18","Landlord and Tenant","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether his Department plans to include lodger landlords in the national database of rogue landlords and property agents.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","145607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907146","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-23","<p>We have interpreted your questions to be about Access to Work workplace assessments.</p><p> </p><p>The data requested are not held centrally and to provide them would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","145582 ; 145584","2018-05-23T15:06:05.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907146/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907146/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907146/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-18","Hyperactivity: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate she has made of the number of requests for workplace assessments for attention deficit hyperactivity disorder in Scotland which were completed in each year since 2015.","false","Biography information for Martin Docherty-Hughes","West Dunbartonshire","Martin Docherty-Hughes","145583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907147","Home Office","false","2018-05-24","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the answer I gave to the Hon. Member for Sheffield Heeley on the 19th March 2018, UIN 132535.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-05-24T15:26:43.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907147/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907147/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907147/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-18","Abortion: Clinics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many submissions his Department has received to the review into harassment and intimidation near abortion clinics; and when he expects to publish the outcome of that review.","false","Biography information for Dr Rupa Huq","Ealing Central and Acton","Dr Rupa Huq","145608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907148","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-23","<p>We have interpreted your questions to be about Access to Work workplace assessments.</p><p> </p><p>The data requested are not held centrally and to provide them would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","145582 ; 145583","2018-05-23T15:06:05.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907148/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907148/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907148/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-18","Hyperactivity: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate she has made of the number of completed workplace assessments for attention deficit hyperactivity disorder in Scotland which were followed up with recommendations for work place changes and support in each year since 2015.","false","Biography information for Martin Docherty-Hughes","West Dunbartonshire","Martin Docherty-Hughes","145584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907149","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-23","<p>The Department does not hold information centrally on the number of delays to the recruitment of overseas doctors as a result of visa restrictions.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises fully the contribution that international doctors working in the National Health Service make towards delivering the high quality compassionate care we all expect.</p><p> </p><p>But it is important that our immigration system works in the national interest, ensuring that employers look first to the United Kingdom resident labour market before recruiting from overseas.</p><p> </p><p>The Department and the Home Office are monitoring the operation of the cap on the number of Certificates of Sponsorship for Tier 2 (General) visas closely to ensure it continues to strike the right balance. The health sector continues to occupy the largest cohort of applications within the Tier 2 (General) limit, taking 39% of available Certificates within the cap in 2017/18.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-05-23T10:49:40.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907149/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907149/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907149/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-18","Doctors: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimate he has made of the number of delays to the recruitment of overseas doctors for reasons of visa restrictions in (a) Ealing hospital and (b) the North West London Trust area in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Dr Rupa Huq","Ealing Central and Acton","Dr Rupa Huq","145609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907150","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-23","<p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State has received 10 written representations from the hospice sector; raising concerns about the potential increase in their costs if they choose to increase pay in line with the proposed Agenda for Change pay rates.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","145389","2018-05-23T12:36:11.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907150/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907150/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907150/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-18","Hospices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether he has received representations from the hospice movement on the effect of the proposed increases in NHS pay on that sector; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","145519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907151","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-23","<p>The proposed Agenda for Change pay framework, which includes contract reform and pay awards over three years, is currently out to consultation with the National Health Service trades unions and the outcome will be known in June.</p><p> </p><p>The Chancellor was explicit that additional funding was tied to extensive reforms to the terms and conditions of staff employed on the Agenda for Change contract.</p><p> </p><p>We are considering the impact of the agreement on non-NHS organisations such as hospices that may be affected by the proposed deal however no decisions have been made.</p><p> </p><p>Staff in hospices do a fantastic job in delivering world-class care. The Department remains fully committed to improving palliative and end of life care.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","145390 ; 145391","2018-05-23T10:44:08.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907151/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907151/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907151/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-18","Hospices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of the effect of the proposed NHS pay increase on voluntary sector hospices.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","145520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907152","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-23","<p>There were an estimated 16,000 SMI benefit claimants in the North West. The Department has written to all SMI benefit claimants on the change to a loan.</p><p> </p><p>Estimates are not available at geographies smaller than Government Office Region on the number of claimants that the Department has written to on the changes to SMI.</p><p> </p><p>Figure rounded to the nearest 1,000 cases.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-05-23T11:51:34.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907152/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907152/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907152/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-18","Support for Mortgage Interest: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many households in (a) the North West, (b) Merseyside, (c) Wirral and (d) Wallasey constituency his Department has written to on the change in support for mortgage interest from a benefit to a loan.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","145559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907153","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-23","<p>The table below gives the Department’s caseload estimates in the North West for Support for Mortgage Interest (SMI) benefit claimants by financial year since 2010.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>2017/18</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Caseload, thousands</p></td><td><p>32</p></td><td><p>30</p></td><td><p>27</p></td><td><p>24</p></td><td><p>22</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>16</p></td><td><p>16</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Table 1: Estimated SMI benefit caseload in the North West by calendar year</em></p><p> </p><p>Estimates are not available at geographies smaller than Government Office Region.</p><p> </p><p>Figures are rounded to the nearest 1,000 cases.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-05-23T11:51:37.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907153/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907153/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907153/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-18","Support for Mortgage Interest: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many households in (a) the North West and (b) Wallasey constituency were in receipt of support for mortgage interest in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","145560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907154","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-23","<p>Data on the number of SMI claimants who have applied for a loan at the geographies requested is not available.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-05-23T11:51:40.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907154/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907154/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907154/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-18","Support for Mortgage Interest: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in receipt of support for mortgage interest resident in (a) the North West, (b) Merseyside, (c) Wirral and (d) Wallasey constituency have applied for a loan under the new scheme.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","145561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907155","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-05-29","<p>The Government has made clear its commitment to crack down on worker exploitation across all sectors of the labour market and welcomes the Labour Market Enforcement Strategy 2018 -19.</p><p> </p><p>There is significant crossover and alignment between this strategy and the government's response to the Taylor Review of Modern Working Practices and subsequent consultations. The Government will publish a response to the Director of Labour Market Enforcement's strategy later this year, once the consultations have closed and the government has considered the responses.</p><p> </p><p>Estimates of the number of jobs paid below National Minimum Wage and National Living Wage by Low Pay Sector (as defined by the Low Pay Commission) are available in Chart 3 on page 10 of the 2017 Government evidence to the LPC report- <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/630197/nmw-nlw-lpc-evidence-compliance-enforcement-2017.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/630197/nmw-nlw-lpc-evidence-compliance-enforcement-2017.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p>These estimates are derived from the ONS Annual Survey of Hours and Earnings 2016; and it should be noted that some textile and clothing occupations are included in the ‘Non-Low Paying Sectors’ category.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will publish new evidence to the Low Pay Commission containing ASHE 2017 estimates of jobs below minimum wage rates and enforcement stats for 2017/18 later this year.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC works closely with other government departments and agencies to tackle National Minimum Wage non-compliance and wider labour market risks, including in the garment and fashion manufacturing industry.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths","145557","2018-05-29T14:29:21.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907155/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907155/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907155/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-18","Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the merits of bringing forward legislative proposals to make leading brands jointly responsible for non-compliance with the national living wage within their supply chains.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","145558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907156","Home Office","false","2018-07-04","<p>The Taskforce consists of approximately 150 staff from a number of areas of UKVI, including Premium Service Centre, Citizenship, Work and Study commands. Staff are flexibly deployed to, and from, locations including Liverpool, Sheffield and Croydon to ensure that the Taskforce is resourced at the necessary grade and location as the need arises.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-07-04T13:15:58.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907156/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907156/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907156/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-18","Home Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many staff in his Department have been transferred to work on the Windrush task force by (a) team, (b) geographic workplace location and (c) grade.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","145572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907157","Home Office","false","2018-06-26","<p>The Department has not estimated the overtime accrued by Taskforce staff.</p><p>There are over 150 people undertaking a variety of working patterns on the Taskforce helpline, booking appointments, making call backs and handling cases. The Department offers staff flexible working arrangements, with staff having the choice of working additional hours, or varying their usual working patterns; and the option to receive overtime payments or accruing time off in lieu.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-06-26T14:07:43.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907157/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907157/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907157/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-18","Home Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate he has made of the overtime accrued by staff in his Department working on the Windrush task force in each of the last four weeks.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","145573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907158","Home Office","false","2018-06-26","<p>The rules governing travel and expenses are contained in the department’s travel and subsistence policy and the Civil Service management code.</p><p>The Department meets the full cost of authorised overnight accommodation, travel and per diem expenses, actually and necessarily incurred by its staff on official business up to the following limits:</p><p>a) Bed and breakfast at max. £125 per night or max. £90 per night (outside London)<br>b) Travel expenses: travel bookings must be standard class and booked as far in advance as possible to take advantage of the cheapest fares; mileage, which is paid at the rate of 23.8p a mile (public transport rate) or, if there is no public transport available, 40p a mile <br>c) The per diem is paid against verified receipts, and covers necessarily incurred additional expenditure (excludes alcohol) at the following rates:<br>• Over 5 hours: up to £4.25<br>• Over 10 hours: up to £9.30<br>• Over 24 hours: up to £26.00</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-06-26T14:13:50.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907158/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907158/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907158/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-18","Home Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the limits for (a) overnight accommodation, (b) travel expenses and (c) per diem entitlements are for staff on the Windrush taskforce who have been redeployed from their normal place of work.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","145574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907159","Home Office","false","2018-06-26","<p>The Department has deployed 68 staff from Liverpool to support the work of the Windrush Taskforce; of those 66 staff have been deployed to Croydon and two to Solihull.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-06-26T14:08:38.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907159/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907159/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907159/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-18","Home Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many staff from the Home Office in Liverpool have been transferred to work on the Windrush taskforce in another Home Office location; and what each of those locations is.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","145575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907160","Home Office","false","2018-07-04","<p>The average compensation payment for wrongful detention is calculated as a ‘Mean’ and a ‘Median’ for FY2015/16 and FY2016/17. These are listed below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>FY2015/16</p></td><td><p>FY2016/17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Mean</p></td><td><p>£24,170</p></td><td><p>£22,957</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Median</p></td><td><p>£20,000</p></td><td><p>£15,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Figures for FY2017/18 have not yet been published.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-07-04T13:14:59.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907160/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907160/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907160/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-18","Detainees: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average compensation payment was to people wrongly detained by the Home Office in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","145576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907161","Home Office","false","2018-05-23","<p>The UK has a proud history of granting asylum to those who need our protection. All claims for asylum are considered on their individual merits in line with Home Office guidance, and where people establish a genuine need for protection, or a well founded fear of persecution, refugee status will be granted.</p><p>The Home Office has plans to improve the speed at which outstanding asylum claims are decided. These include rolling recruitment campaigns to maintain decision maker levels, a staff retention strategy to ensure it retains its highly skilled asylum decision makers, and the further expansion of digital processes to increase caseworking flexibility.</p><p>Furthermore, the Home Office issues an information leaflet to asylum claimants at the point of claim that outlines the process and their responsibilities.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-05-23T14:51:49.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907161/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907161/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907161/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-18","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Refugee Action report, Waiting in the dark, published on 16 May 2018, what steps he plans to take to improve the (a) quality and (b) speed of the asylum decision making process; and if he will provide independent support and information to asylum seekers about the asylum system when they apply for asylum.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","145566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907162","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-23","<p>Further to the announcement of 9 May, the Government is considering the most effective way to implement the ‘golden hello’ incentive scheme for postgraduate nursing students.</p><p> </p><p>These payment incentives offer £10,000 to future postgraduates who completed courses funded by loans in the 2018/19 academic year. The golden hello payments are anticipated to be contingent on these graduates working in specific fields of the health and care sector including mental health, learning disability and community, including district, nursing.</p><p> </p><p>The detail of the scheme is being developed by the Department. Officials will engage with stakeholders as part of finalising proposals; including determining whether it is in the best interests of the National Health Service to split out the numbers eligible for a payment determined by branch of nursing. The conclusions of this will inform assessments of the potential impact of such incentives.</p><p> </p><p>Our cost projections were based on current numbers, and if the number of students increases we will consider how best to implement the incentives to continue meeting objectives to fill hard-to-recruit places.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","145580 ; 145581","2018-05-23T15:08:41.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907162/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907162/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907162/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-18","Health Professions: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Minister for Health of 9 May 2018, Official Report, column 844, whether the £9.1 million in golden hellos to postgraduate students in specific hard-to-recruit disciplines such mental health, learning and disability, and district nursing will be made available to applicants for the 2018-19 academic year.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","145579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907163","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-23","<p>Further to the announcement of 9 May, the Government is considering the most effective way to implement the ‘golden hello’ incentive scheme for postgraduate nursing students.</p><p> </p><p>These payment incentives offer £10,000 to future postgraduates who completed courses funded by loans in the 2018/19 academic year. The golden hello payments are anticipated to be contingent on these graduates working in specific fields of the health and care sector including mental health, learning disability and community, including district, nursing.</p><p> </p><p>The detail of the scheme is being developed by the Department. Officials will engage with stakeholders as part of finalising proposals; including determining whether it is in the best interests of the National Health Service to split out the numbers eligible for a payment determined by branch of nursing. The conclusions of this will inform assessments of the potential impact of such incentives.</p><p> </p><p>Our cost projections were based on current numbers, and if the number of students increases we will consider how best to implement the incentives to continue meeting objectives to fill hard-to-recruit places.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","145579 ; 145581","2018-05-23T15:08:41.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907163/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907163/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907163/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-18","Nurses: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Minister for Health of 9 May 2018, Official Report, column 844, how the £9.1 million in golden hellos will be divided between applicants for (a) mental health nursing, (b) learning and disability nursing and (c) district nursing.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","145580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907164","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-23","<p>Further to the announcement of 9 May, the Government is considering the most effective way to implement the ‘golden hello’ incentive scheme for postgraduate nursing students.</p><p> </p><p>These payment incentives offer £10,000 to future postgraduates who completed courses funded by loans in the 2018/19 academic year. The golden hello payments are anticipated to be contingent on these graduates working in specific fields of the health and care sector including mental health, learning disability and community, including district, nursing.</p><p> </p><p>The detail of the scheme is being developed by the Department. Officials will engage with stakeholders as part of finalising proposals; including determining whether it is in the best interests of the National Health Service to split out the numbers eligible for a payment determined by branch of nursing. The conclusions of this will inform assessments of the potential impact of such incentives.</p><p> </p><p>Our cost projections were based on current numbers, and if the number of students increases we will consider how best to implement the incentives to continue meeting objectives to fill hard-to-recruit places.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","145579 ; 145580","2018-05-23T15:08:41.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907164/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907164/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907164/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-18","Nurses: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Minister for Health of 9 May 2018, Official Report, column 844, what estimate his Department has made of the number of students who will study nursing as a result of the offer of golden hellos for certain disciplines.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","145581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907165","Department for Education","false","2018-05-23","<p>The Department for Education has not undertaken a review of the current approach to pupils with hyperactivity.</p><p> </p><p>The 0-25 Special Educational Needs and Disability (SEND) Code of Practice provides statutory guidance and is applicable across the range of SEND. Where pupils with hyperactivity experience learning difficulties that call for additional or different educational provision to that required by other children, the Code of Practice will apply.</p><p> </p><p>Schools are required to identify and address the SEND of the pupils they support and to use their best endeavours to make sure that a child or young person who has SEND gets the support they need. In inspecting a school, Ofsted must consider how well the school meets the needs of the range of pupils at the school, including specifically those with SEND.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-05-23T13:28:54.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907165/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907165/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907165/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-18","Pupils: Hyperactivity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 17 May 2018 to Question 143877, when last his Department reviewed the adequacy of the current approach to pupils with hyperactivity.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","145616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907166","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-05-23","<p>An explanation of the types of cost are as follows:</p><p> </p><ul><li><strong>Ad hoc: </strong>Requests from MoJ for additional services and works outside of the fixed fee.</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li><strong>Hard Variable and Soft Variable</strong>: Services that are not included within the fixed fee, e.g. vandalism. “Hard” variable services relate to the physical fabric of a building (e.g. building maintenance). “Soft” variable services relate to the services that support a building (e.g. cleaning)</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li><strong>Management Variable:</strong> Management costs associated with variable costs.</li></ul>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-05-23T16:40:05.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907166/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907166/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907166/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-05-18","Ministry Of Justice: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 27 April 2018 to Question 136385, on Ministry of Justice: Contracts, what types of costs are included under the (a) ad hoc, (b) hard variable, (c) soft variable and (d) management variable categories.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","145598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907167","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-05-23","<p>The Ministry’s proven reoffending rates are measured from the date of sanction for those receiving a non-custodial sentence and the date of release for those receiving custodial sentences, in line with most international studies.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry takes this approach because it mainly reflects the period when an offender is most at risk of re-offending in the community.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-05-23T16:39:00.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907167/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907167/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907167/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-05-18","Reoffenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, for what reasons reoffending rates for prison sentences and community sentences are not both counted from the time of sentencing.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","145599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907168","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-23","<p>I have responded to the hon. Member’s letter today.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-05-23T15:05:13.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907168/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907168/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907168/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-18","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, when he plans to respond to the letter from the hon. Member for Glasgow North West dated 27 April 2018 on Serco Group PLC’s contract with Public Health England.","false","Biography information for Carol Monaghan","Glasgow North West","Carol Monaghan","145588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907169","Department for Education","false","2018-05-23","<p>The 2016 Education and Adoption Act<a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-18%20drafts/145610%20QC%20210518.docx#_ftn1" target="_blank">[1]</a> placed a duty on the Secretary of State to make an academy order in respect of any maintained school that has been judged inadequate by Ofsted, to enable it to become an academy and receive additional support from a sponsor.</p><p> </p><p>Between 18 April 2016, when this power came into force, and 1 May 2018, the department has issued 426 academy orders to inadequate local authority maintained schools. Of these, 218 have since opened as sponsored academies. In all cases, we will ensure that there is appropriate support in place to secure improvement until the school converts. This can be from the preferred sponsor or through another multi-academy trust or teaching school alliance, or direct from the local authority. Some schools do not proceed to conversion, either because they close or merge or because they improve sufficiently and are removed from special measures. 21 have had their academy orders revoked, either due to subsequent Ofsted inspections, or closure or merger.<strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-18%20drafts/145610%20QC%20210518.docx#_ftnref1" target="_blank">[1]</a> Section 4(A1) of the Academies Act 2010, as inserted by the Education and Adoption Act 2016.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-05-23T14:38:58.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907169/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907169/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907169/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-18","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many directive academy orders have been issued to maintained schools that Ofsted has rated as inadequate pursuant to s4(A1) of the Academies Act 2010; and how many of those schools have subsequently opened as sponsored academies.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","145610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907170","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-23","<p>Defra does not hold up to date estimates of the numbers of animal rescue homes, and therefore cannot provide an estimate of the proportion that are members of the Association of Dogs and Cats Homes.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-23T16:16:55.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907170/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907170/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907170/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-18","Association of Dogs and Cats Homes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what information his Department holds on the proportion of animal rescue centres in England which are members of the Association of Dogs and Cats Homes.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","145617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907171","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-24","<p>Section 15 of the Road Safety Act 2006 has not been commenced. For commencement, primary legislation would be required to amend section 16 and no timescales are currently planned for this. To date, the Government has not supported the mandatory use of alcohol interlocks as the disadvantages associated with such a scheme, including lack of evidence of long term behavioural change, ease of circumventing the device, and high installation and maintenance costs, together outweigh any potential benefits.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government will continue to enforce vigorously against drink drivers, and changes in the law in April 2015 made it a requirement for high risk offenders to undertake medical tests to ensure they are not still dependent before they are allowed to drive again.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-05-24T10:46:28.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907171/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907171/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907171/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-18","Driving Under Influence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the timescale is for the commencement of s15 of the Road Safety Act 2006.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","145569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907172","Treasury","false","2018-05-23","<p>We will launch the UK Shared Prosperity Fund following the UK’s departure from the European Union.</p><p>The implementation period included within the draft Withdrawal Agreement with the EU means that we will see all parts of the UK receive their full allocation of structural funds from the EU’s 2014-2020 budget.</p><p>The Industrial Strategy White Paper set out that we intend to consult this year on the precise design and priorities for the fund. Further details on the operation of the UK Shared Prosperity Fund will be set out following this consultation.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-05-23T13:07:07.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907172/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907172/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907172/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-18","EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 16 May 2018 to Question 143241, whether Shared Prosperity Fund will be operational on 30 March 2019.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","145618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907173","Department for Education","false","2018-05-29","<p>The Department for Education recognises the valuable contribution made to schools in England by overseas-trained teachers. Teachers from the non-EEA countries Australia, Canada, New Zealand and the USA may apply to have their Qualified Teacher Status (QTS) automatically recognised, as these countries are considered to have education systems suitably similar to that of England. The decision on which non-EEA countries are eligible to apply for QTS automatically is based upon a comprehensive comparative analysis of international initial teacher training systems, conducted by the UK National Academic Recognition Information Centre (NARIC). This assessment concluded that there were no other countries with teacher training systems sufficiently similar to England’s to allow their teachers to apply directly without further training or conditions. However, if teachers from non-EEA countries have significant teaching experience, they may be able to undergo a school-based assessment of their abilities, known as the ‘Assessment Only’ route, which can lead to the award of QTS.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-05-29T11:54:31.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907173/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907173/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907173/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-18","Teachers: Qualifications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of expanding the list of non-EEA countries that are recognised for the purposes of awarding Qualified Teacher Status in England.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","145585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907174","Department for Education","false","2018-05-23","<p>The Department is currently assessing the evidence gathered during an engagement process, including a call for evidence, to support decisions on the content of Relationships Education for primary schools and Relationships and Sex Education for secondary schools, and on the status of Personal, Social, Health and Economic education.</p><p> </p><p>The Department plans to publish the results of the call for evidence shortly alongside a consultation on draft regulations and accompanying statutory guidance, before laying the regulations in the House for debate.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is working towards schools being able to teach the new subjects from September 2019.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-05-23T16:57:21.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907174/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907174/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/907174/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-18","Sex and Relationship Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what progress has been made on introducing compulsory Relationships and Sex Education in schools by September 2019.","false","Biography information for Ged Killen","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Ged Killen","145615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906288","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-25","<p>Defra officials have been working with a range of stakeholders in planning for the illegal wildlife trade conference in October, and we are keen to include as wide a range of species and geographies in the conference as possible. We have not yet reached a decision on the final agenda.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley",,"2018-05-25T11:07:13.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906288/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906288/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906288/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-17","Nature Conservation: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions he has had on placing wildlife crime on sovereign base areas in Cyprus on the agenda for the Illegal Wildlife Trade Conference in October 2018.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","145292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906289","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-24","<p>The Government’s statutory Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy, published in April 2017, outlines £1.2 billion of funding that may be invested in cycling and walking in England over the period to 2021. Funding for cycling infrastructure in the rest of the UK is a matter for the devolved administrations. Since the Strategy’s publication, the Government has made further support available for cycling and walking infrastructure in England, through the National Productivity Investment Fund, Transforming Cities Fund and Clean Air Fund. Decisions on allocating funding for dedicated cycle networks are for local authorities, who allocate and/or bid for funding alongside other local priorities. In addition, the Department for Transport is providing 44 local authorities in England with access to expert support to assist in the development of ten-year Local Cycling and Walking Infrastructure Plans. This support will enable authorities to map their future cycle networks and to prioritise future investments.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-05-24T10:29:43.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906289/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906289/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906289/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-17","Cycleways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what funding his Department plans to allocate to dedicated cycle networks similar to London's cycle superhighways in (a) cities and (b) towns throughout the UK.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","145394"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906290","Home Office","false","2018-05-24","<p>Facial recognition systems can be used to compare people in public spaces to images on a pre-determined list and provide suggested matches to a human operator. The rate of suggested matching will depend on the system, the images and the circumstances of the deployment. They will produce false positive matches which it would be for the operator to consider including any follow up procedure.</p><p>The decision to deploy such systems is an operational one for police forces but they must comply with Data Protection Legislation and show regard to the Surveillance Camera Code of Practice, the Information Commissioner’s Code of Practice and other relevant policies and legislation.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-05-24T15:57:57.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906290/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906290/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906290/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-17","Police: Biometrics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if he will take steps to ensure that the facial recognition software that law enforcement bodies use is accurate.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","145395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906291","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-22","<p>The Parliamentary Under Secretary of State (Lord O’Shaughnessy) responded to the hon. Member on 21 May.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-05-22T14:14:05.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906291/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906291/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906291/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-17","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, when he plans to respond to the letter from the hon. Member for Glasgow North West dated 25 April 2018 on myalgic encephalomyelitis.","false","Biography information for Carol Monaghan","Glasgow North West","Carol Monaghan","145353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906292","Department for Education","false","2018-05-31","<p>The Department recognises that looked after children are amongst the most vulnerable in our society. That is why the School Admissions Code requires admission authorities of all schools to prioritise looked after children and previously looked after children in their admissions criteria.</p><p> </p><p>Local authorities (LAs) have the power to direct the admission authority for any maintained school in England to admit a child who it ‘looks after’, even if that school is full. Therefore, the Department does not hold information on individual applications to maintained schools made on behalf of the looked after child. The Department itself can direct a maintained school if required, but so far it has not had to.</p><p> </p><p>For academies, trusts and LAs work together at a local level to prioritise the admission of looked after children. As a last resort, a LA can request a direction for the academy to admit from the Secretary of State, via the Education and Skills Funding Agency (ESFA). The ESFA has collected and recorded data on such direction requests since March 2017. Since then, there have been 28 requests. However, the ESFA have successfully worked with LAs and academies to ensure that a formal direction was only required in four cases.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-05-31T16:46:46.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906292/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906292/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906292/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906292/answer/previousversion/60401","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906292/answer/previousversion/60401","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2018-05-17","Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 14 May 2018 to Question 142462, how many schools have refused to admit looked-after or previously looked after children and were subsequently directed by his Department to do so in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","145341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906293","Department for Education","false","2018-05-25","<p>School admissions are a local matter and applications are dealt with at a local level. The department does not hold information around the outcome of individual applications.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise that looked after children are amongst the most vulnerable in our society. The School Admissions Code requires admission authorities of all schools, including academies, to give highest priority in their admissions criteria to looked after children and previously looked after children.</p><p> </p><p>Where a school refuses to admit a looked after or previously looked after child, they can be directed to do so. The Education and Skills Funding Agency, who consider direction requests on behalf of my Rt hon. Friend the Secretary of State, have successfully worked with local authorities, and free schools to ensure such cases are resolved without the need for a direction to be issued.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-05-25T08:48:14.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906293/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906293/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906293/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-17","Free Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many looked-after children were refused a place at a free school in each of the last three years; and which free schools have refused to admit looked-after or previously looked after children and were subsequently directed by his Department to do so in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","145342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906294","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-22","<p>​We assess all applications very carefully against the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria and human rights and international humanitarian law considerations are important parts of that assessment. We have no information to suggest that UK supplied equipment has been used in contravention of the Criteria. We continue to keep the situation under constant review.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-05-22T14:54:26.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906294/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906294/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906294/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-17","Israel: Arms Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what role his Department plans to play in reviewing UK arms exports to Israel as a result of the events in Gaza of 14 May 2018.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","145278"
